Every design principle is applied deliberately. Here is the rationale behind each decision.
Correct chart selection. Line chart for the sales trend because sales is continuous over time and direction matters. Horizontal bar for regions and categories because the bars are sorted by value and the labels are text — horizontal orientation prevents label rotation and makes comparison faster. Bar chart for segment return risk because we are comparing discrete groups, not a trend. Stacked bar for shipping because we need both total order volume and the internal delay distribution simultaneously. No pie charts, no dual axes, no decorative charts.
Clear hierarchy. The page title sits alone at the top, followed by the data context line. Filters come next as a distinct band. KPIs sit below filters — they update to reflect the current filter state and give the at-a-glance answer before any chart is read. Charts are then arranged with the two most important views (trend and regional) in the wider top row, and the three supporting views in equal columns below.
Minimal clutter. Grid lines are light hairlines on the value axis only — none on the category axis. Chart borders are removed from axes. No tick marks. No background fills on chart areas. No decorative icons inside charts. The insight strip below each chart delivers the business interpretation in plain text so the chart itself can stay uncluttered.
Consistent color usage. Blue (#2a78d6) consistently means "the leading item" — the top region, the primary trend line. Technology is always blue, Furniture always amber, Office Supplies always green across all charts. The shipping delay colour is a traffic light: green → light green → light blue → amber → red, ordered by severity. Red in the return rate chart means above average. These colour meanings never change as filters are applied.
Proper labels and readable titles. Every chart has a plain-language title ("Profit by category") and a question it answers ("Which categories drive profit or loss?"). Axis labels use business units — ₹ Crore, not raw numbers. Return rate axis is explicitly labelled "Return rate (%)" so the unit is never ambiguous.
Appropriate sorting. Regional bars are sorted descending by sales so the best performer is always at the top. Category bars are sorted descending by profit. The segment return risk bar places Home Office first because it has the highest return rate — the most urgent item is first in reading order. Ship modes are ordered from most to least delayed so Standard Class is always on the left where the eye lands first.
Useful filters. Four filters — Year, Region, Category, Segment — all drive every chart and every KPI card simultaneously. The description line below the title updates to state how many orders match the current selection. A Reset button restores the full view in one click.
Zero-baseline scales — no misleading axes. Every chart starts at zero. The return rate chart is capped at 8% — enough headroom to show variation without truncating the bars. The sales trend y-axis always starts at zero regardless of filter selection.
Business interpretation. Each chart has a plain-English insight strip that updates when filters change — it states the actual finding, not just the number ("Standard Class: 27% of orders arrive slow or very slow. Same Day delivers 98% within 2 days"). The three summary notes at the bottom explicitly label business significance: Strength, Watch, and Action.
